WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:05.200
High up on the Tibetan Plateau, surrounding&nbsp;
the sacred summit of Mount Kailash,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:05.200 --> 00:00:10.560
the ridges and valleys are giving birth to the&nbsp;
headwaters of South Asia’s great rivers. Alongside&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:16.800
tributaries that feed the Brahmaputra and Ganges,&nbsp;
the meltwater from glaciated gullies give life to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.800 --> 00:00:22.240
the Indus River, which will then go on a journey&nbsp;
through the world’s tallest mountains, arid plains&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:27.600
and lush wetlands, supporting the livelihood of&nbsp;
hundreds of millions of people along the way.&nbsp;

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:33.360
Rushing down from the northern edge of the&nbsp;
Himalayas at over 5,500 meters in elevation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:36.800
headwaters of the Indus River have carved a&nbsp;
path along the&nbsp;

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:41.520
collision belt of the Indian and Eurasian&nbsp;
tectonic plates. Flowing northwest,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:47.200
the Indus River steadily grows as glaciers&nbsp;
from giants like K2 and Nanga Parbat drain&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:51.840
into its valley. Winding through the disputed&nbsp;
Kashmir region, the Indus River eventually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:57.840
hits the Karakoram Range and the Hindu Kush Mountains,&nbsp;
forcing the river's path towards the Indian Ocean.&nbsp;

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:02.720
As the rocky outcrops of Tibet give way to&nbsp;
the Pothohar Plateau and the river's elevation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.720 --> 00:01:08.160
drops to a mere 200 meters above sea level,&nbsp;
the 2.7 kilometer long Tarbela Dam suddenly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:12.880
stands in its way. It holds back the river&nbsp;
in an enormous 50 kilometer long reservoir,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:12.880 --> 00:01:18.160
creating hydroelectric power and smoothing out&nbsp;
the annual fluctuation in discharge of the river.&nbsp;

00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:23.120
Below the spillways, the course of the Indus&nbsp;
River reaches its second phase, entering Punjab,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:28.480
the breadbowl of Pakistan. A compound word of&nbsp;
the Persian “Panj” and “Ab” meaning the “land&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:34.000
of 5 waters”, it describes the largest tributaries&nbsp;
of the Indus drainage basin that feed the main river.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.360
Here, the Sutlej, whose drainage basin is separated&nbsp;
by only a single ridge on the Tibetan Plateau,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:42.640
finally unites with the Indus.
Between these 5 tributaries,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.640 --> 00:01:47.280
the single largest interconnected irrigation&nbsp;
network of the planet has fueled an immense&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:51.840
irrigated landscape. Despite sitting on the&nbsp;
western fringe of the South Asian monsoon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:56.960
corridor and therefore only receiving marginal&nbsp;
rainfall, dozens of major dams, hundreds of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:56.960 --> 00:02:03.360
canals and thousands of distributaries are fueling&nbsp;
agriculture, in an otherwise semi-arid landscape.&nbsp;

00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:08.880
Today about 270 million people have built their&nbsp;
livelihood around this irrigation system, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:13.920
has not just transformed the central Pakistani&nbsp;
plain but also the river’s delta. After passing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:13.920 --> 00:02:20.080
the Thar Desert, the sediments of the Indus River&nbsp;
have built a 240 kilometer wide alluvial fan.&nbsp;

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:25.280
Back in the 19th century, mangrove forests&nbsp;
once buffered the coast from tidal swells and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.280 --> 00:02:30.160
storm surges and even grew through steady&nbsp;
sediment deposits. Since then however,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:34.320
upstream water management has reduced the&nbsp;
freshwater and sediment reaching the sea,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:40.480
and mangroves shrank from about 400,000 to only&nbsp;
50,000 hectares over the 20th century. Since the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.480 --> 00:02:46.160
1990s, restoration efforts have recovered some&nbsp;
area, but with less freshwater and silt arriving,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:50.320
the delta faces erosion and saltwater&nbsp;
intrusion, and remains a vulnerable habitat.&nbsp;

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:55.360
If you want to learn more about the greatest rivers&nbsp;
of our planet, I have a full playlist here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:59.120
or watch what YouTube thinks is best for&nbsp;
you here. See you in the next one, cheers.

